understanding the words they said:
When the doc said we need to tense up the muscles before taking the punch he is specifically referring to the 4 major abdominal muscles which are external oblique, internal oblique, transverse abdominis and Rectus abdominis( which is responsible for the 8 packs).
Now coming to the next thing which is peritonitis, we can consider a balloon in the abdomen and the abdominal organs as small beads. Now if you shake the balloon with the beads in it then the beads would move around and displace from their original position. Now if we consider this scenario with our own body, the result would fatal as the organs would be flying around everywhere even if we do simple movement. So our body adapts to this situation by attaching the organs to the abdomen. The way they attach is complex but in simple terms imagine pushing those beads into the balloon from outside, even though the beads are pushed from the outside they end up inside the balloon but with a layer of the rubber around them. This balloon is called as peritoneum. Occasionally due to trauma blood stars to leak from the abdominal organs. Due to the trauma this balloon might get damaged and the blood would start leaking into the balloon. This pooling of blood is very dangerous because the the blood could get infected and damage the other abdominal organs(also called as viscera). The term ‘itis’ in peritonitis means inflammation, therefore peritonitis translates to inflammation of peritoneum which again is in response to various other factors induced due to the trauma.
Hope this helps😊

The guy who punched Houdini was an amateur boxer. The punch in his stomach really had nothing to do with Houdini’s death. Most scholars on Magic and Houdini recognize that Houdini was already having issues with his appendix. But he wasn’t one to go and seek help. The punch to his stomach only gave him a reason to ignore the underlying issue.

By the time he was convinced to go to the hospital, it had already been some time after the punch. The main reason he went was because he could barely walk anymore, and collapsed after a show.

Now, the book you mentioned makes the claim he was poisoned. The reason being that after the surgery, he was starting to recover quickly. However, that all switched all at once and he died shortly after. So he had made a recovery, but after that recovery from a successful surgery, he all of a sudden turned deathly ill and passed away.

So no, it wasn’t from a punch. The issue had been with his appendix and a punch will not make your appendix burst. At most, the punch just gave him an excuse to not see the doctors as he could rationalize the pain. It was a short time after that that Houdini would collapse after a show, and be taken to the hospital, where he had a successful surgery and he began to recover. Either there was a complication, or as the book you suggested claims, he was poisoned, and that was the ultimate cause of his death.

Harry Houdini died of peritonitis, secondary to a ruptured appendix at 1:26 p.m. on October 31, 1926 in Room 401 at Detroit's Grace Hospital, aged 52. In his final days, he optimistically held to a strong belief that he would recover, but his last words before dying were reportedly, "I'm tired of fighting."[18] Eyewitnesses to an incident at Houdini's dressing room in the Princess Theatre in Montreal gave rise to speculation that Houdini's death was caused by a McGill University student, J. Gordon Whitehead, who delivered a surprise attack of multiple blows to Houdini's abdomen.[70]

The eyewitnesses, students named Jacques Price and Sam Smilovitz (sometimes called Jack Price and Sam Smiley), proffered accounts of the incident that generally corroborated one another. Price describes Whitehead asking Houdini "if he believed in the miracles of the Bible" and "whether it was true that punches in the stomach did not hurt him". He then delivered "some very hammer-like blows below the belt". Houdini was reclining on a couch at the time, having broken his ankle while performing several days earlier. Price states that Houdini winced at each blow and stopped Whitehead suddenly in the midst of a punch, gesturing that he had had enough, and adding that he had had no opportunity to prepare himself against the blows, as he did not expect Whitehead to strike him so suddenly and forcefully. Had his ankle not been broken, he would have risen from the couch into a better position to brace himself.[70][71]

Throughout the evening, Houdini performed in great pain. He was unable to sleep and remained in constant pain for the next two days, but did not seek medical help. When he finally saw a doctor, he was found to have a fever of 102 °F (39 °C) and acute appendicitis, and advised to have immediate surgery. He ignored the advice and decided to go on with the show.[72][73] When Houdini arrived at the Garrick Theater in Detroit, Michigan, on October 24, 1926, for what would be his last performance, he had a fever of 104 °F (40 °C). Despite the diagnosis, Houdini took the stage. He was reported to have passed out during the show, but was revived and continued. Afterwards, he was hospitalized at Detroit's Grace Hospital.[70]

It is not entirely clear what relationship the encounter in the dressing room had on Houdini's eventual death.[70] As Snopes points out, the relationship between blunt trauma and appendicitis is not clear. One theory suggests that Houdini was unaware that he was suffering from appendicitis. If he had not realized that his stomach pains were symptomatic of appendicitis, he would not have appreciated the potentially critical effect of the blows to his abdomen.[70]

After taking statements from Price and Smilovitz, Houdini's insurance company concluded that the death was due to the dressing-room incident and paid double indemnity.[72]

Houdini died from, as you note, diffuse streptococcal peritonitis.  This was a consequence of his appendix having ruptured indirectly.  It must be noted, however, that the man who punched Houdini (allegedly Canadian George Whitehead) may or may NOT have had any effect on the famous magician.  

What actually caused Houdini's death was his stubborn refusal to seek medical care when he knew he needed it.  A physician told him to get to a hospital nearly a week before he died, but being the live-or-die showman he was, he insisted that the show go on.  In his final performance, at the Princess theatre, in Detroit, he spiked a very high fever, and was not physically capable of fighting-off the staff who insisted on rushing him to the hospital there.   Alas, of course, the intervention was too late.

Surgeons opened his abdomen, and closed him immediately realizing that death was eminent.  Houdini died with his beloved wife, Bess, by his side.

While it's interesting, the book you reference, "The Secret Life of Houdini," is largely made up of fantasy and supposition.

The best Houdini biography to date is that written by Pulitzer prize-winning biographer Ken Silverman.  The second best and less academic in approach is Melbourn Christopher's Houdini biography.

I taught martial Arts for over 25yrs and used Houdini's stomach punch as a training tool. Even if Houdini wouldn't have gotten caught off guard he would have still most likely ended up having to have had that surgery eventually if he would have continues to let people punch him. Like most of us our bodies can only handle some much pounding. And the six pack guy could have gotten himself seriously hurt because he didn't blow out when the SmarterEveryDay guy punched him. If you are a fighter than you know that when you get punched in the gut to always blowout while tensing up the abdominal muscles. This keeps the air that is trapped in your lungs from compressing and temporally paralyzing the lungs and also from damaging any internal organs. Also one thing to remember try not to get hit in the sternum. You can't protect that area no matter how strong your abs are. Also a good area to hit if you need to take someone down.

If you look at the death certificate, it says the peritonitis was due to streptococcus, which is a type of gram positive bacteria that can be found as natural bacteria in the gut. Indeed streptococcus are lactic bacteria (survive without air) and include the enterococcus group which accounts for 90% or normal bacteria in the gut. It's possible that he had his gut ruptured. This would allow natural flora to infect the peritoneum. He probably needed a good dose of antibiotics alongside surgery.
